<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-11-04T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-11-04T03:00:00-05:00" n="251" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d251">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">861.77 Chinese Eastern/434:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-04T16:00:00+08:00">November 4, 1929—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received November 5—10:20 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>961. My 951, November 2, 3 p.m. Following from American Consul at Harbin:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“November 4, 3 p.m. Fuchin some days ago occupied by Soviet
                                    forces but now again in the hands of Chinese troops. This raid
                                    and loss of practically entire Chinese gunboat fleet have
                                    depressed all local Chinese circles and produced panicky feeling
                                    at Harbin, inhabitants Taheiho evacuated, they and other
                                    residents along the Amur River fear Soviet offensive when Amur
                                    freezes which will be within a period of a week.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>